<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="137" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
The new species is very similar externally to 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. languidum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="languidum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. languidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Yunnan) and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. puetzi" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="puetzi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. puetzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Sichuan), but can be recognised by the emarginated anterior margin of frons (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 2–8" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 2 - 8. 2 rotten bamboo trap (Photo by Mr. Yu-Jie Cai from Guizhou, Leishan County, Xiannuetang at 1 May 2021) 3 habitat of H. flavoterminale (Photo by Mr. Qin-Hao Zhao from Sichuan, Dujiangyan City, Mt Qingchengshan at 1 Aug. 2021) 4 living H. flavoterminale on decaying tree (Photo by Mr. Qin-Hao Zhao from Sichuan, Dujiangyan City, Mt Qingchengshan at 1 Aug 2021) 5 living H. languidum sp. nov. running on decaying tree with fungi during the night (Photo by Mr. Liang Tang from Yunnan, Lushui County, Yaojiapin at 21 Jun 2010) 6 living H. excellens on rotten bamboo (Photo by Mr. Liang Tang from Anhui, Tangkou Town, Jiulongpu at 1 Jul 2020) 7 living H. guizhouense hunting for maggots in rotten bamboo (Photo by Mr. Yu-Jie Cai from Guizhou, Leishan County, Xiannuetang at 2 May 2021) 8 living H. klapperichi sucking tree sap (Photo by Mr. Zhong Peng from Guangxi, Jinxiu County, ' 16 km' at 13 Jul 2014)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1075.75799.figures2-8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/620005" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">8</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 9–12" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 9 - 12. Head of species of subgenus Hesperosoma Hesperosoma 9 H. chenchangchini sp. nov. 10 H. puetzi 11 H. xizangense sp. nov. 12 H. languidum sp. nov. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1075.75799.figures9-12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/620006" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">9</figureCitation>
), as well as by the different shape of the aedeagus, especially the paramere, which is broad and truncate apically. Additionally, the head is wider, 1.29 times as wide as long (1.14-1.16 in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. puetzi" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="puetzi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. puetzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 1.22 in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. languidum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="languidum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. languidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.), the mandibles are relatively darker (relatively lighter in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. puetzi" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="puetzi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. puetzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. languidum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="languidum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. languidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.) and the legs are relatively darker (relatively lighter in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. puetzi" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="puetzi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. puetzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. languidum" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="languidum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. languidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.).
</paragraph>
